requirement_issues.requirement_text: The design of the wet well control system shall provide for the safety and protection of pumping station operators, maintenance personnel, and the public from hazards that may result from its operation.

issues.description: The requirement does not specify what constitutes 'hazards' or define specific safety measures that must be implemented.
issues.suggested_fix: Define specific hazards (e.g., electrical shock, toxic gases, drowning, equipment failure) and specify corresponding safety measures for each.

issues.description: No performance metrics or safety thresholds are provided to guide implementation.
issues.suggested_fix: Include specific thresholds and performance requirements for hazard detection and system response.

issues.description: The requirement cannot be objectively tested without specific safety criteria and measurable outcomes.
issues.suggested_fix: Define measurable safety criteria such as response times for hazard detection, specific alarm thresholds, and safety shutdown procedures with pass/fail criteria for each safety function.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for monitoring and reporting the level of liquid in the wet well.

issues.description: The meaning of 'reporting' is unclear (e.g., destination, frequency, format).
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify where the level is reported, at what intervals, and in which format.

issues.description: No sampling rate or precision is specified for liquid level monitoring.
issues.suggested_fix: Define the required sampling frequency and resolution (e.g., ±0.1 ft every second).

issues.description: Test cases cannot be designed without defined thresholds or reporting intervals.
issues.suggested_fix: Provide test scenarios detailing expected behavior under various liquid levels.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for monitoring and reporting the state of each pump and whether it is currently running or not.

issues.description: Use of 'state of each pump' versus 'running or not' is inconsistent and may confuse implementers.
issues.suggested_fix: Unify terminology to clearly specify which pump states are monitored (e.g., running, available, faulted).

issues.description: Reporting mechanism and frequency are not defined.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify how often pump state is polled and to whom it is reported.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The control system shall activate a visual and audible alarm when a hazardous condition exists.

issues.description: The requirement does not define what constitutes a 'hazardous condition' - this is too vague for implementation.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify all conditions that trigger alarms: high liquid level, pump seal failure, motor overheating, unauthorized entry, etc.

issues.description: Alarm duration, silencing procedures, and acknowledgment are not specified.
issues.suggested_fix: Define alarm behavior such as latching, reset, and acknowledgment requirements.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The control system shall switch each submersible pump on or off in a timely fashion depending on the level of liquid within the wet well.

issues.description: The term 'timely fashion' is subjective and cannot be implemented without specific time requirements.
issues.suggested_fix: Define specific response times, e.g., 'within 2 seconds of level threshold being reached'.

issues.description: Liquid level thresholds for switching on/off pumps are not defined.
issues.suggested_fix: Define numeric values or reference configuration settings for lead and lag pump activation.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well reservoir contains two submersible pumps sized to provide a fixed capacity.

issues.description: The required fixed capacity (flow rate) of the pumps is not specified.
issues.suggested_fix: Include the design flow rate per pump (e.g., 500 GPM each).

requirement_issues.requirement_text: It has a ventilation fan that is oriented to direct fresh air into the wet well rather than just exhaust from the well.

issues.description: Pronoun 'It' is unclear; it should specify the reservoir or control system.
issues.suggested_fix: Refer explicitly to the wet well reservoir.

issues.description: No operational or control requirements are given for the ventilation fan.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify whether the system must monitor or control the fan.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: A float switch is used to determine the depth of liquid currently in the wet well.

issues.description: REQ-030 mentions 'level switches' while this mentions 'float switch' - unclear if these are the same or different components.
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify if float switch and level switches are the same component or specify the relationship between them.

issues.description: Does the float switch provide continuous depth measurement or discrete threshold events?
issues.suggested_fix: Clarify whether continuous level data is required or only level-event signaling.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: Each submersible pump shall be equipped with a moisture sensor that detects the occurrence of an external pump seal failure.

issues.description: Detection frequency and sensor accuracy are not specified.
issues.suggested_fix: Define sampling interval and sensitivity of moisture detection.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: Should a seal failure be detected, the pump shall be turned off and alarm state set.

issues.description: Which alarm state and which system component handles the shutdown and alarm?
issues.suggested_fix: Specify that PumpControlUnit must shut down the pump motor and notify the alarm controller.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide automated operation.

issues.description: This requirement is duplicated by REQ-022 with identical wording.
issues.suggested_fix: Remove duplicate requirement or clarify if there are different aspects of automated operation being specified.

issues.description: The requirement does not specify the scope or rules of automated operation.
issues.suggested_fix: Define the scenarios and logic for automated operation (e.g., pump control based on liquid level, alarm handling).

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide local manual override operation.

issues.description: This requirement is duplicated by REQ-021 with nearly identical meaning.
issues.suggested_fix: Remove duplicate requirement or clarify different aspects of manual override operation.

issues.description: The requirement does not describe how manual override will be implemented or its interaction with automated operation.
issues.suggested_fix: Specify the mechanisms for manual override (e.g., physical buttons, UI controls) and any safety constraints.

requirement_issues.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide local observational operation.

missing_requirements.description: Missing methane gas concentration monitoring and control requirements
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall continuously monitor methane gas concentration levels in the wet well using a methane sensor. When methane concentration exceeds 25% of the Lower Explosive Limit (LEL), the system shall activate the ventilation fan and trigger visual/audible alarms. When concentration exceeds 50% LEL, the system shall shut down all pumps and activate emergency ventilation protocols.
missing_requirements.rationale: Business rules explicitly state hazardous gas concentrations can exist, and system context includes methane sensor, but no requirements define monitoring thresholds or actions. This is critical for operator safety and regulatory compliance.

missing_requirements.description: Missing specific liquid depth threshold values and configuration
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall define and maintain configurable depth thresholds: Lead Pump Depth (minimum operational level), Lag Pump Depth (secondary pump activation level), High Depth (alarm level), and Low Depth (pump shutoff to prevent dry running). These values shall be configurable by authorized maintenance personnel and shall maintain the hierarchy: High Depth > Lag Depth > Lead Depth > Low Depth.
missing_requirements.rationale: Requirements reference these depth levels but don't specify actual values or configuration mechanisms. Critical for proper pump operation and preventing overflow/dry running.

missing_requirements.description: Missing user authentication and authorization requirements
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall enforce role-based access control requiring users to authenticate before performing manual override operations, adjusting configuration parameters, acknowledging alarms, or accessing historical data. Pumping Station Operators shall have access to manual mode and basic operations. Maintenance Personnel shall have additional access to configuration, diagnostics, and system parameters. All user actions and authentication attempts shall be logged with timestamp and user identification.
missing_requirements.rationale: Business rules emphasize security considerations and authorized personnel access, but no requirements define authentication mechanisms. Critical for preventing unauthorized system modifications and ensuring audit trails.

missing_requirements.description: Missing pump motor temperature threshold and monitoring specifications
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall continuously monitor pump motor temperature using integrated temperature sensors. When motor temperature exceeds 80°C (176°F), the system shall activate warning indicators. When temperature exceeds 90°C (194°F), the system shall immediately shut down the affected pump, activate alarms, and start the alternative pump if liquid level requires pumping.
missing_requirements.rationale: Domain model has overheated attribute and requirements mention temperature monitoring, but specific thresholds and sensor requirements are missing. Essential for equipment protection and preventing failures.

missing_requirements.description: Missing runtime data tracking and storage requirements
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall track and store runtime data for each pump including: total operating hours, number of start/stop cycles, runtime per session, and cumulative runtime difference between pumps. Runtime data shall be stored for minimum 2 years and be accessible for maintenance analysis and regulatory reporting. Runtime equalization shall maintain pump runtime difference within 10% of total operating time.
missing_requirements.rationale: Requirements mention runtime equalization but lack specifics on data tracking, storage duration, and equalization criteria. Important for maintenance planning and regulatory compliance.

missing_requirements.description: Missing power failure detection and backup system integration
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall detect main power failures and automatically switch to backup power system within 5 seconds. During backup power operation, the system shall continue critical monitoring functions and maintain pump operations with priority given to preventing overflow conditions. The system shall monitor backup power status and activate alarms when backup power capacity drops below 30 minutes of operation.
missing_requirements.rationale: System context mentions power backup system but no requirements address power failure scenarios. Critical for continuous operation during power outages in this safety-critical system.

missing_requirements.description: Missing access door sensor integration and monitoring requirements
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall monitor the wet well access door using an integrated door sensor. When the door is opened by authorized personnel, the system shall automatically activate ventilation fan and log the access event. Unauthorized door opening (without proper authentication) shall trigger immediate visual and audible alarms and notify relevant personnel.
missing_requirements.rationale: System context mentions access door sensor and requirements reference monitoring unauthorized entry, but specific door sensor integration and authorized access procedures are not defined.

missing_requirements.description: Missing system self-diagnostic on startup or return from power loss
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: Upon startup or restoration of power, the wet well control system shall perform self-diagnostic tests on all subsystems (sensors, pumps, motors, fan, alarms) and display any faults on the control display panel; normal automated operations shall not commence until all identified faults are cleared or bypassed by authorized maintenance personnel.
missing_requirements.rationale: No requirements address system startup procedures or self-testing capabilities. Critical for ensuring system reliability and detecting component failures before they cause operational problems.

missing_requirements.description: Missing pump capacity specification and performance monitoring requirements
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: Each submersible pump shall have a minimum capacity of [X] gallons per minute at standard operating head. The system shall monitor actual pump performance against rated capacity and alert maintenance personnel when performance degrades below 90% of rated capacity. Pump capacity shall be sufficient to handle peak inflow conditions while maintaining liquid levels within operational thresholds.
missing_requirements.rationale: Domain model includes pump capacity attribute and requirements mention fixed capacity, but actual capacity values and performance monitoring are not specified. Important for ensuring adequate pumping capability.

missing_requirements.description: Missing alarm acknowledgment and escalation procedures
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall require manual acknowledgment of all alarm conditions by authorized personnel. Unacknowledged critical alarms (high level, pump failure, gas detection) shall escalate after 15 minutes by activating additional notification methods and logging escalation events. Acknowledged alarms shall remain visible until the underlying condition is resolved.
missing_requirements.rationale: Requirements define alarm activation but not acknowledgment or escalation procedures. Important for ensuring alarms receive proper attention and response in this safety-critical system.

missing_requirements.description: Missing requirements for detecting sensor failures and handling them
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The wet well control system shall perform continuous self-diagnostics on all sensors (float switch, moisture sensor, methane sensor, access door sensor) and, upon detecting a sensor failure or loss of communication, shall set an alarm state, notify maintenance personnel, and inhibit automated pump operation until the fault is resolved.
missing_requirements.rationale: Sensor failures can lead to undetected hazards such as overflow, dry-run, gas buildup, or unauthorized entry, and must be detected and handled to maintain system safety.

missing_requirements.description: Missing requirements for event logging and historical data retention for compliance and diagnostics
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The control system shall log all critical events—including pump start/stop actions, alarm activations, sensor readings (liquid level, moisture, temperature, gas concentration), configuration changes, and user operations—with timestamps; logs shall be retained for a minimum of 90 days and be accessible via the control display panel or exportable in CSV format.
missing_requirements.rationale: Regulatory agencies (EPA, DEP) require audit trails of system operations and events for compliance and post-incident analysis.

missing_requirements.description: Missing performance requirement for system response time to liquid level threshold events
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The control system shall detect a liquid level crossing of any threshold (lead pump depth, lag pump depth, allowable high liquid depth) and issue the corresponding control action (pump start/stop, alarm activation) within 2 seconds of the threshold event.
missing_requirements.rationale: Timely response to level changes is vital to prevent overflow or dry-run conditions that could damage equipment or pose safety hazards.

missing_requirements.description: Missing requirement for remote monitoring or SCADA integration for centralized control and data acquisition
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The wet well control system shall provide a standardized network interface (e.g., Modbus/TCP, OPC-UA) to integrate with plant SCADA systems, enabling remote monitoring of liquid level, pump states, alarm statuses, and access door integrity.
missing_requirements.rationale: Stakeholders often require remote monitoring and centralized control via existing SCADA infrastructure for operational oversight and coordination.

missing_requirements.description: Missing requirement for pump maintenance state tracking
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall track and display maintenance states for each pump (e.g., scheduled maintenance, in repair, out of service) and prevent automatic operation of pumps in maintenance mode while notifying operators of reduced system capacity.
missing_requirements.rationale: The domain model includes pump availability but doesn't account for maintenance states which are crucial for operational planning and preventing equipment damage during maintenance.

missing_requirements.description: Missing requirement for system startup and shutdown procedures
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall provide documented startup and shutdown procedures accessible through the control display panel to ensure safe operation during maintenance or emergencies, including proper sequencing of pump operations and ventilation activation.
missing_requirements.rationale: Essential for operator safety and system integrity during maintenance operations and emergency situations, but not specified in requirements.

missing_requirements.description: Missing requirement for data backup and recovery
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall automatically backup operational data, configuration parameters, and event logs daily to non-volatile storage and provide recovery procedures in case of system failure, with backup integrity verification.
missing_requirements.rationale: Critical for maintaining historical data, system configuration, and compliance records, but not addressed in current requirements.

missing_requirements.description: Missing requirement for alarm prioritization
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall prioritize alarms based on severity (e.g., gas leak > high liquid level > pump failure > maintenance alerts) and handle concurrent alarms appropriately, displaying the highest priority alarm prominently while maintaining visibility of all active alarms.
missing_requirements.rationale: Multiple alarm types exist but no requirements govern their interaction or prioritization, which is essential for operator response in emergency situations.

missing_requirements.description: Missing requirement for regulatory compliance reporting and data retention
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall generate and maintain regulatory compliance reports for EPA and DEP agencies including: pump operation logs, alarm events, maintenance activities, environmental monitoring data, and system performance metrics. Data shall be retained for minimum 5 years in tamper-proof format and be readily accessible for regulatory inspections and audits.
missing_requirements.rationale: Business rules emphasize EPA and DEP compliance but no requirements specify reporting obligations or data retention policies. Essential for regulatory compliance and avoiding violations.

missing_requirements.description: Missing requirement for pump alternation logic
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall alternate the lead pump between the two submersible pumps after each complete pump cycle to ensure equal wear, with the alternation pattern configurable and the current lead pump status displayed on the control panel.
missing_requirements.rationale: While equalizing run time is mentioned, specific alternation logic isn't defined, which is critical for equipment longevity and maintenance planning.

missing_requirements.description: Missing requirement for sensor calibration monitoring and management
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall monitor and alert when sensors (float switch, moisture sensor, methane sensor) require calibration based on time intervals or drift detection, maintain calibration history logs, and provide calibration procedures through the control interface.
missing_requirements.rationale: Critical for measurement accuracy and regulatory compliance, but sensor calibration requirements are not addressed in current specifications.

missing_requirements.description: Missing requirement for pump dry-run protection
missing_requirements.suggested_requirement: The system shall detect and prevent pump dry-run conditions that could damage equipment through independent verification methods beyond float switches, including motor current monitoring and vibration analysis, with immediate pump shutdown and alarm activation.
missing_requirements.rationale: Critical for equipment protection as dry-run conditions can cause catastrophic pump failure, but only basic level monitoring is specified in current requirements.

domain_model_issues.description: Requirements REQ-018 and REQ-032 mention monitoring pump motor temperatures for overheating, but no temperature sensor exists in the domain model.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add TemperatureSensor class with attributes for temperature readings and methods for detecting overheating conditions.

domain_model_issues.description: REQ-036 mentions monitoring access door for unauthorized entry via broken electrical circuit, but no access door component exists in the domain model.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add AccessDoor class with attributes for door state and electrical circuit status, and methods for monitoring unauthorized entry detection.

domain_model_issues.description: REQ-016 requires monitoring for unauthorized entry/trespass, but no dedicated security monitoring component exists.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add SecuritySystem class to handle unauthorized entry monitoring and integrate with alarm system.

domain_model_issues.description: REQ-019 and REQ-034 mention storing and displaying historical operational parameters, but no data storage component exists.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add HistoricalDataStore class to manage storage and retrieval of historical operational data with methods for data logging and retrieval.

domain_model_issues.description: No class exists for monitoring environmental conditions (temperature, humidity, gas) as mentioned in requirements.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add EnvironmentalSensor with attributes and methods to report environmental data.

domain_model_issues.description: No class represents configuration for depth thresholds (lead, lag, high) that are referenced throughout requirements.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Introduce ThresholdSettings to encapsulate configurable depth thresholds with appropriate getter/setter methods.

domain_model_issues.description: The reservoir should track current liquid level as this is a fundamental parameter mentioned in multiple requirements.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add liquidLevel attribute of type Double to WetWellReservoir class along with maxCapacity and associated methods.

domain_model_issues.description: REQ-023 and REQ-029 require equalizing run times between pumps, but no run time tracking attributes exist in pumps or control unit.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add runTime attribute of type Long to SubmersiblePump class and corresponding tracking in PumpControlUnit (e.g., runTimeCounters map) to track total operational time.

domain_model_issues.description: REQ-048, REQ-049, and REQ-050 mention lead pump depth, lag pump depth, and high level alarm depth thresholds but these configuration parameters are not stored in the float switch.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add leadPumpDepth, lagPumpDepth, and highLevelAlarmDepth attributes to FloatSwitch class.

domain_model_issues.description: FloatSwitch measures liquid depth in the reservoir but has no direct relationship with WetWellReservoir.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add association relationship between FloatSwitch and WetWellReservoir since the switch is physically located in and measures the reservoir.

domain_model_issues.description: PumpControlUnit monitors and controls PumpMotor but no association is defined.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add an association between PumpControlUnit and PumpMotor (and/or SubmersiblePump) to represent control relationship.

domain_model_issues.description: LevelSwitch duplicates functionality of FloatSwitch regarding depth detection and has incorrect relationship with WetWellControlSystem instead of PumpControlUnit.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Consolidate LevelSwitch and FloatSwitch into a single DepthSwitch class or clearly define separate roles, and associate with PumpControlUnit for pump start indication.

domain_model_issues.description: FloatSwitch methods checkLeadPumpDepth, checkLagPumpDepth, and checkHighLiquidDepth don't return values or trigger actions as required.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Change these methods to return boolean values indicating if thresholds are exceeded, or add event notification mechanism to trigger pump control actions.

domain_model_issues.description: The WetWellReservoir class has no attributes or methods, despite being a central component of the system.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add attributes (e.g., maxCapacity, currentLiquidLevel) and methods (e.g., getLiquidLevel) to represent its functionality.

domain_model_issues.description: The SubmersiblePump class has no methods, despite requirements specifying pump control actions (e.g., turn on/off).
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add methods (e.g., start(), stop(), isRunning()) to align with requirements.

domain_model_issues.description: The monitorUnauthorizedEntry() method does not align with REQ-036, which specifies detection via broken electrical circuit on access door.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Update the method to reflect the specific detection mechanism or integrate with AccessDoor class for proper circuit monitoring.

domain_model_issues.description: The attribute name 'liquidDepth' is inconsistent with REQ-040, which uses 'depth of influent'.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Rename the attribute to match the terminology in REQ-040 (e.g., 'influentDepth') for consistency.

domain_model_issues.description: Attribute sealFailure duplicates data from composed MoistureSensor.leakDetected.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Remove sealFailure from SubmersiblePump and rely on MoistureSensor for leak detection to avoid data duplication.

domain_model_issues.description: The manual override method exists but lacks parameters to specify what operations can be overridden and how.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add parameters to specify which components can be controlled manually (pumps, alarms, etc.) and their desired states.

domain_model_issues.description: ControlDisplayPanel supports only a single depth attribute and lacks history display capabilities.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add methods and attributes to handle multiple parameters and historical data display capabilities.

domain_model_issues.description: VentilationFan lacks control methods if fan operation must be managed.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Add startFan() and stopFan() methods if control is required by the system.

domain_model_issues.description: WetWellControlSystem has many responsibilities violating single responsibility principle.
domain_model_issues.suggested_fix: Refactor into specialized controllers (e.g., LevelController, AlarmController) to better distribute responsibilities.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The design of the wet well control system shall provide for the safety and protection of pumping station operators, maintenance personnel, and the public from hazards that may result from its operation.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-001 [Priority: High; Source: Safety Standards; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Ensure system safety and regulatory compliance; Quality Attributes: Safety]: The wet well control system shall provide safety and protection of pumping station operators, maintenance personnel, and the public from operational hazards. Acceptance Criteria: (1) System detects hazardous conditions within 1 second, (2) Safety alarms activate within 1 second of detection, (3) System passes safety certification testing, (4) Meets all regulatory requirements.
requirement_completeness.rationale: This safety requirement lacks essential metadata, specific acceptance criteria, and measurable performance requirements. Safety requirements need precise timing specifications, testable criteria, regulatory compliance verification, and clear dependencies for proper implementation and validation.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for monitoring and reporting the level of liquid in the wet well.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-002 [Priority: High; Source: Operator Requirements; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Accurate liquid level monitoring essential for proper pump operation and overflow prevention; Quality Attributes: Performance, Accuracy]: The control system shall continuously monitor and report liquid level in the wet well with ±0.1 feet accuracy. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Level measurement accuracy within ±0.1 feet, (2) Level readings updated every 5 seconds, (3) Level data logged for historical tracking. Dependencies: REQ-008.
requirement_completeness.rationale: The requirement lacks specific accuracy requirements, update frequency, clear acceptance criteria, and dependencies on level sensing components. These specifications are essential for testability and implementation.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control system shall be responsible for monitoring and reporting the state of each pump and whether it is currently running or not.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-003 [Priority: High; Source: Operator Requirements; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Pump state monitoring critical for automated operation and fault detection; Quality Attributes: Timeliness, Reliability]: The control system shall continuously monitor and report the operational state (running/stopped/failed) of each submersible pump. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Pump state updated within 2 seconds of status change, (2) State information displayed on control panel, (3) State changes logged with timestamp.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Needs specific timing requirements and clear definition of what 'state' includes beyond just running status. Missing acceptance criteria make the requirement difficult to test and verify.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control system shall activate a visual and audible alarm when a hazardous condition exists.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-004 [Priority: High; Source: Safety Standards; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Immediate alarm notification critical for operator safety and emergency response; Quality Attributes: Safety, Responsiveness]: The control system shall activate both visual indicator lights and audible alarm within 1 second when any hazardous condition is detected. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Alarms activate within 1 second of hazard detection, (2) Visual alarm visible from 50 feet, (3) Audible alarm audible at 85dB at 3 feet, (4) Alarms remain active until manually acknowledged.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Safety-critical alarms need specific performance criteria including activation time, visibility/audibility requirements, and reset behavior. Missing these specifications makes the requirement impossible to properly test and verify.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The control system shall switch each submersible pump on or off in a timely fashion depending on the level of liquid within the wet well.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-005 [Priority: High; Source: Operator Requirements; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Timely pump switching prevents overflow and dry running; Quality Attributes: Performance, Responsiveness]: The control system shall switch each submersible pump on or off within 5 seconds based on liquid level thresholds. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Pump starts within 5 seconds when level reaches start threshold, (2) Pump stops within 5 seconds when level reaches stop threshold, (3) System responds to level changes within operating range. Dependencies: REQ-008, REQ-048, REQ-049.
requirement_completeness.rationale: The term 'timely fashion' is vague and needs specific time requirements. Dependencies on level sensing requirements should be explicit for proper system integration.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well reservoir contains two submersible pumps sized to provide a fixed capacity.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-006 [Priority: Medium; Source: Design Specification; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Design; Rationale: Dual pumps provide redundancy and capacity for peak flow conditions; Quality Attributes: Capacity, Reliability]: The wet well reservoir shall contain exactly two submersible pumps, each sized to provide [X] GPM capacity. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Two pumps physically installed in reservoir, (2) Each pump rated for specified GPM capacity, (3) Pumps positioned to prevent interference.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Needs specific capacity values and clearer requirement structure with proper 'shall' statement format. Missing capacity specifications make the requirement unverifiable.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: It has a ventilation fan that is oriented to direct fresh air into the wet well rather than just exhaust from the well.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-007 [Priority: Medium; Source: Design Specification; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Design; Rationale: Fresh air injection prevents dangerous gas accumulation and maintains safe working environment; Quality Attributes: Airflow, Safety]: The wet well reservoir shall contain one ventilation fan oriented to direct fresh air into the wet well providing minimum [X] CFM airflow. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Fan provides minimum specified CFM airflow into well, (2) Fan operates continuously during system operation, (3) Airflow direction verified during installation.
requirement_completeness.rationale: The pronoun 'It' is ambiguous and needs clear actor identification. Requires specific airflow requirements and proper requirement structure format for implementation and testing.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: A float switch is used to determine the depth of liquid currently in the wet well.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-008 [Priority: High; Source: Sensor Selection Document; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Accurate liquid depth measurement essential for automated pump control; Quality Attributes: Accuracy, Reliability]: The control system shall use a float switch to determine the liquid depth in the wet well with ±0.1 feet accuracy. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Float switch provides depth measurement accurate to ±0.1 feet, (2) Switch responds to depth changes within 2 seconds, (3) Switch operates reliably over full depth range.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Needs proper 'shall' format, clear actor identification, and specific accuracy requirements for the measurement system. Missing these makes the requirement difficult to implement and test.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: Each submersible pump shall be equipped with a moisture sensor that detects the occurrence of an external pump seal failure.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-009 [Priority: High; Source: Safety Requirements; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Early seal failure detection prevents pump damage and environmental contamination; Quality Attributes: Reliability, Responsiveness]: Each submersible pump shall be equipped with a moisture sensor that detects external pump seal failure within 30 seconds. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Sensor detects moisture presence indicating seal failure, (2) Detection occurs within 30 seconds of failure, (3) Sensor signal transmitted to control system, (4) False positive rate less than 1%.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Needs specific detection time requirements and performance criteria to ensure effective seal failure detection. Missing timing specifications make it impossible to verify proper operation.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: Should a seal failure be detected, the pump shall be turned off and alarm state set.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-010 [Priority: High; Source: Safety Requirements; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Immediate pump shutdown prevents further damage and environmental impact; Quality Attributes: Safety, Responsiveness]: When a seal failure is detected, the control system shall immediately shut down the affected pump and activate alarm state within 2 seconds. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Pump shutdown within 2 seconds of seal failure detection, (2) Alarm state activated simultaneously, (3) Pump remains offline until manual reset, (4) Event logged with timestamp. Dependencies: REQ-009.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Needs specific response time and clear identification of the acting system. Dependencies on moisture detection should be explicit for proper system integration and safety response.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide automated operation.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-011 [Priority: High; Source: Automation Spec; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Automated operation ensures continuous operation and reduces operator workload; Quality Attributes: Autonomy, Reliability]: The wet well control system shall provide fully automated operation mode that controls pump switching based on liquid levels without operator intervention. Acceptance Criteria: (1) System operates pumps automatically based on level thresholds, (2) No operator intervention required during normal operation, (3) System handles pump failures by switching to backup pump, (4) Mode selectable via control panel.
requirement_completeness.rationale: The requirement is too vague and needs specific definition of what 'automated operation' includes with measurable acceptance criteria for testing and verification.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide local manual override operation.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-012 [Priority: Medium; Source: Operator Requirements; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Manual override necessary for maintenance, testing, and emergency situations; Quality Attributes: Usability, Safety]: The wet well control system shall provide local manual override operation allowing operators to directly control pump operation from the control panel. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Manual controls accessible at control panel, (2) Override mode disables automatic operation, (3) Individual pump start/stop controls available, (4) Override mode clearly indicated on display, (5) Safety interlocks remain active.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Needs specific definition of manual override capabilities and safety considerations to ensure operator control while maintaining safety functions.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide local observational operation.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-013 [Priority: Low; Source: Monitoring Spec; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Observational mode allows monitoring system status during maintenance without risk of inadvertent operation; Quality Attributes: Observability, Usability]: The wet well control system shall provide local observational operation mode that displays system parameters without allowing control functions. Acceptance Criteria: (1) All system parameters visible on display, (2) Control functions disabled in observational mode, (3) Mode clearly indicated on display, (4) Real-time and historical data accessible.
requirement_completeness.rationale: The term 'observational operation' is unclear and needs specific definition of what can be observed and what functions are available in this mode.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall start the pump motors to prevent the wet well from running over and stop the pump motors before the wet well runs dry.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-014 [Priority: High; Source: Operational Safety Spec; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Prevents property damage from overflow and pump damage from dry running; Quality Attributes: Safety, Performance]: The wet well control system shall start pump motors when liquid level reaches high threshold to prevent overflow and stop pump motors when level reaches low threshold to prevent dry running. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Pumps start when level reaches [X] feet, (2) Pumps stop when level reaches [Y] feet, (3) Level thresholds configurable, (4) Override protection prevents dry running, (5) Response time within 5 seconds. Dependencies: REQ-008.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Needs specific level thresholds and timing requirements. The conditions need to be measurable and testable for proper implementation and verification.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall keep track of whether or not each motor is running.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-015 [Priority: High; Source: Monitoring Spec; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Motor status tracking essential for automated control and maintenance scheduling; Quality Attributes: Traceability, Reliability]: The wet well control system shall continuously monitor and record the running status of each pump motor with status updates every 2 seconds. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Motor status updated every 2 seconds, (2) Status changes logged with timestamp, (3) Running time accumulated for each motor, (4) Status displayed on control panel.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Needs specific update frequency and definition of how the tracking is implemented and used for system operation and maintenance.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall monitor the pumping site for unauthorized entry or trespass.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-016 [Priority: Medium; Source: Security Requirements; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Security monitoring protects equipment and prevents tampering or vandalism; Quality Attributes: Security, Reliability]: The wet well control system shall monitor the pumping site for unauthorized entry through access door sensors and activate security alarms when intrusion is detected. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Door sensors detect unauthorized opening, (2) Security alarm activated within 2 seconds, (3) Intrusion events logged with timestamp, (4) False alarm rate less than 5%. Dependencies: REQ-036, REQ-037.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Security requirements need specific detection methods and performance criteria. Dependencies on specific security sensors should be identified for proper implementation.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall monitor the environmental conditions within the wet well.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-017 [Priority: Medium; Source: Environmental Monitoring Spec; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Environmental monitoring ensures safe working conditions and prevents hazardous gas accumulation; Quality Attributes: Safety, Reliability]: The wet well control system shall monitor environmental conditions including temperature, humidity, and gas levels within the wet well. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Temperature monitored ±2°F accuracy, (2) Humidity monitored ±5% accuracy, (3) Hazardous gas detection with alarm, (4) Readings updated every 30 seconds, (5) Environmental alarms activated when thresholds exceeded.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Needs specific definition of which environmental conditions are monitored and the accuracy/alarm requirements for each parameter.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall monitor the physical condition of each pump for the existence of moisture and excessive temperatures.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-018 [Priority: High; Source: Motor Protection Spec; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Pump condition monitoring prevents failures and extends equipment life; Quality Attributes: Reliability, Safety]: The wet well control system shall continuously monitor each pump for moisture (indicating seal failure) and excessive temperatures (>85°C) with alarms activated when thresholds are exceeded. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Moisture detection within 30 seconds, (2) Temperature monitoring ±2°C accuracy, (3) Temperature alarm at 85°C, (4) Automatic pump shutdown on critical conditions, (5) Condition data logged. Dependencies: REQ-009.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Needs specific temperature thresholds and timing requirements for condition monitoring and alarm activation to ensure effective pump protection.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall display real time and historical operational parameters.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-019 [Priority: Medium; Source: HMI Requirements; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Parameter display supports operation monitoring and troubleshooting; Quality Attributes: Usability, Performance]: The wet well control system shall display real-time operational parameters (liquid level, pump status, alarms) updated every 5 seconds and historical data for the past 30 days. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Real-time data updated every 5 seconds, (2) Historical data stored for 30 days minimum, (3) Parameters include level, pump status, run times, alarms, (4) Data accessible via control panel display.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Needs specific definition of which parameters are displayed, update frequency, and data retention requirements for proper implementation and testing.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide an alarm feature.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-020 [Priority: High; Source: Safety Standards; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Alarm system critical for safety and operational awareness; Quality Attributes: Safety, Reliability]: The wet well control system shall provide comprehensive alarm features including visual and audible alarms for high level, pump failure, seal failure, and security breaches. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Visual and audible alarms for all critical conditions, (2) Alarm acknowledgment capability, (3) Alarm history logging, (4) Configurable alarm thresholds, (5) Alarm testing functionality.
requirement_completeness.rationale: Too vague and needs specific definition of what alarm features are provided and for which conditions to enable proper implementation and testing.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide a manual override of the site.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-021 [Priority: Medium; Source: Operator Requirements; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Manual override essential for maintenance, testing, and emergency operations; Quality Attributes: Safety, Usability]: The wet well control system shall provide manual override capability allowing operators to directly control all site operations including pump start/stop, alarm reset, and mode selection. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Manual control of individual pumps, (2) Alarm acknowledgment and reset, (3) Operating mode selection, (4) Override status clearly indicated, (5) Safety interlocks maintained. Dependencies: REQ-012.
requirement_completeness.rationale: This appears to duplicate REQ-012. Needs clarification of scope and specific override capabilities provided or consolidation with similar requirements.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall provide automated operation of the site.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-022 [Priority: High; Source: Automation Spec; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Automated operation ensures continuous operation and optimal pump utilization; Quality Attributes: Autonomy, Reliability]: The wet well control system shall provide fully automated site operation including automatic pump control based on liquid levels, pump rotation for runtime equalization, and automatic fault handling. Acceptance Criteria: (1) Automatic pump switching based on levels, (2) Pump runtime equalization, (3) Automatic backup pump activation, (4) Unattended operation capability, (5) Fault detection and response. Dependencies: REQ-011.
requirement_completeness.rationale: This appears to duplicate REQ-011. Needs clarification of scope or consolidation with similar requirements to avoid redundancy and confusion.

requirement_completeness.requirement_text: The wet well control system shall equalize the run time between the pumps.
requirement_completeness.suggested_improvement: REQ-023 [Priority: Medium; Source: Maintenance Spec; Version: 1.0; Status: Draft; Type: Functional; Rationale: Runtime equalization extends pump life and ensures equal wear; Quality Attributes: Reliability, Efficiency]: The wet well control system shall equalize run time between pumps by alternating which pump starts first, maintaining runtime difference within 10% of total runtime. reasoning.domain_model: I combined the two meaningful models (deepseek and openai) by taking the best elements from each. From MODEL 2, I adopted the PumpControlUnit and WetWellReservoir classes which provide better separation of concerns and clearer organization. From MODEL 1, I kept the separate PumpMotor class as it better represents the physical separation between pump and motor components. I harmonized method signatures by using the more specific parameter types and return types where appropriate. I combined attributes from both models, using boolean types for state indicators and Double for measurements. The relationships were structured to show proper composition vs association, with the reservoir containing pumps and fans, pumps containing motors and sensors, and the control unit managing displays and alarms. I excluded MODEL 3 as it was empty, and resolved conflicts by choosing the most comprehensive and realistic representations from the other two models.
reasoning.analysis:
Analysis aggregated using claude with specialized component processing:
- requirement_completeness: All three LLM assessments (Claude, DeepSeek, and OpenAI) provided identical requirement completeness evaluations, demonstrating remarkable consistency in their analysis. This convergence strengthens confidence in the assessment's accuracy. The conservative completeness scores (20-25%) appropriately reflect the significant gaps in essential requirement metadata and specifications. Key patterns identified across all requirements include: (1) Universal absence of critical metadata (priority, rationale, source, status, version, type), (2) Missing measurable acceptance criteria essential for testing and verification, (3) Lack of specific performance requirements and timing constraints, (4) Insufficient dependency identification between related requirements, (5) Several duplicate requirements requiring consolidation (REQ-011/022, REQ-012/021, REQ-015/025, REQ-020/035, REQ-023/029, REQ-014/024, REQ-019/041, REQ-009/038), and (6) Vague language requiring quantification for implementation. The assessment maintains the conservative approach by preserving the low completeness scores, as safety-critical systems like wet well pump controls require comprehensive, testable, and traceable requirements to ensure proper operation and regulatory compliance.
- requirement_issues: I combined the requirement issues from all three sources by: 1) Preserving all unique issues while merging similar ones with the most comprehensive descriptions, 2) Resolving conflicts by maintaining the highest severity levels when issues overlapped, 3) Standardizing terminology and affected model elements for consistency, 4) Ensuring critical safety and operational issues maintain MUST FIX severity while less critical issues are marked SHOULD FIX or SUGGESTION. The final list contains 92 total issues across 50 requirements, with conflicts and duplications clearly identified, ambiguous terms flagged for clarification, and missing contextual information highlighted for completion.
- missing_requirements: All three source analyses (claude, deepseek, and openai) provided identical missing requirements lists with exactly the same 22 requirements (MR1-MR22). Since there were no differences in descriptions, categories, severities, suggested requirements, affected model elements, or rationales between the sources, no merging or combination was necessary. The comprehensive list preserves all unique missing requirements identified across the three analyses, covering critical safety gaps (methane monitoring, dry-run protection), operational requirements (depth thresholds, pump alternation), security needs (authentication, access control), and compliance obligations (regulatory reporting, data retention). Each requirement maintains its original detailed rationale and comprehensive scope.
- domain_model_issues: I combined the three domain model analyses by: 1) Consolidating similar issues (e.g., AccessDoor/DoorSensor, HistoricalDataStore/DataLogger) while preserving the most detailed descriptions, 2) Merging related attribute issues (e.g., pump run time tracking across SubmersiblePump and PumpControlUnit), 3) Combining relationship and class structure issues around LevelSwitch/FloatSwitch duplication, 4) Preserving unique issues from each analysis, 5) Standardizing severity levels based on requirement criticality, and 6) Ensuring all affected requirements are captured. The final list addresses 22 distinct issues covering missing classes, incomplete implementations, inconsistent relationships, and structural problems that collectively impact the system's ability to meet its operational requirements.
